Normalize via `trim().toLowerCase()` FIRST, then `distinctUntilChanged` suppresses re-emissions for equivalent queries — "Alice", "alice ", and "ALICE" all collapse to a single request.

You combine three operators in a pipe: `debounceTime(ms)` waits for the keystrokes to pause, `distinctUntilChanged()` suppresses re-emissions of the same string, and `switchMap(project)` cancels any previous inner observable when a new outer value comes in.

```ts
import { Observable } from 'rxjs';
import { debounceTime, distinctUntilChanged, switchMap } from 'rxjs/operators';

declare function search$(q: string): Observable<string[]>;

export const results$ = (input$: Observable<string>): Observable<string[]> =>
  input$.pipe(
    debounceTime(300),
    distinctUntilChanged(),
    switchMap((q: string) => search$(q))
  );
```

Swap `switchMap` for `mergeMap` and you get a race condition; swap for `concatMap` and you get a queue that never drops stale requests.

Same three-operator shape as a typeahead — `debounceTime` + `distinctUntilChanged` + `switchMap` — but the inner observable is a filter over a known dataset rather than a network call.

```ts
import { Observable, of } from 'rxjs';
import { debounceTime, distinctUntilChanged, switchMap } from 'rxjs/operators';

interface Row {
  id: string;
  name: string;
}

const rows: Row[] = [
  { id: '1', name: 'Alice' },
  { id: '2', name: 'Bob' },
  { id: '3', name: 'Carol' },
];

export const filtered$ = (
  term$: Observable<string>
): Observable<Row[]> =>
  term$.pipe(
    debounceTime(150),
    distinctUntilChanged(),
    switchMap((q: string) =>
      of(rows.filter((r: Row) => r.name.toLowerCase().includes(q.toLowerCase())))
    )
  );
```

Even for a synchronous filter, `switchMap(of(...))` preserves the same cancel-on-new-value semantic if you later swap in an async source.

Same pattern. `switchMap` here means: if another keystroke arrives before the save completes, cancel the in-flight save and kick off a new one with the latest draft. That's usually what you want for drafts — you'd rather save the latest than commit a stale write.

```ts
import { Observable } from 'rxjs';
import { debounceTime, distinctUntilChanged, switchMap } from 'rxjs/operators';

interface SaveAck {
  savedAt: number;
}

declare function persistDraft$(body: string): Observable<SaveAck>;

export const autosave$ = (
  draft$: Observable<string>
): Observable<SaveAck> =>
  draft$.pipe(
    debounceTime(500),
    distinctUntilChanged(),
    switchMap((body: string) => persistDraft$(body))
  );
```

If you need every intermediate save to land (e.g. for an audit log), use `concatMap` instead so drafts queue up and run serially in order.

Start the pipeline the same way — debounce, distinct, switch — but make the inner observable a page-1 fetch so new queries always start fresh.

```ts
import { Observable } from 'rxjs';
import { debounceTime, distinctUntilChanged, switchMap } from 'rxjs/operators';

interface Page<T> {
  items: T[];
  nextCursor: string | null;
}

interface Invoice {
  id: string;
  amountCents: number;
}

declare function fetchInvoices$(
  query: string,
  cursor: string | null
): Observable<Page<Invoice>>;

export const invoicePage1$ = (
  query$: Observable<string>
): Observable<Page<Invoice>> =>
  query$.pipe(
    debounceTime(300),
    distinctUntilChanged(),
    switchMap((q: string) => fetchInvoices$(q, null))
  );
```

Pagination beyond page 1 would be a separate stream driven by a `scroll$` or `loadMore$` subject — keep the typeahead focused on first-page freshness.

You don't need `fromEvent` — just pipe straight off the observable you were given.

```ts
import { Observable } from 'rxjs';
import { debounceTime, distinctUntilChanged, switchMap } from 'rxjs/operators';

interface Hit {
  id: string;
  label: string;
}

declare function suggest$(q: string): Observable<Hit[]>;

export function wire(
  text$: Observable<string>
