The `$` suffix on `text$` and return type is a community convention — signals "this is an observable" without cluttering the type annotation.

In v7 operators are standalone functions composed through the observable's `.pipe(...)` method — prototype patching is gone.

```ts
import { Observable } from 'rxjs';
import { debounceTime, distinctUntilChanged, switchMap } from 'rxjs/operators';

declare function lookup$(q: string): Observable<string[]>;
declare const input$: Observable<string>;

export const results$: Observable<string[]> = input$.pipe(
  debounceTime(300),
  distinctUntilChanged(),
  switchMap((q: string) => lookup$(q))
);
```

Pre-v5.5 you imported `'rxjs/add/operator/debounceTime'` for the side-effect of patching `Observable.prototype`. v7 removed that path entirely.

`.do(...)` was renamed to `tap(...)` in rxjs@5.5 and is imported from `'rxjs/operators'`.

```ts
import { Observable } from 'rxjs';
import { debounceTime, distinctUntilChanged, switchMap, tap } from 'rxjs/operators';

declare function runSearch$(q: string): Observable<string[]>;
declare const search$: Observable<string>;

export const out$: Observable<string[]> = search$.pipe(
  debounceTime(300),
  distinctUntilChanged(),
  tap((q: string) => console.log('searching for', q)),
  switchMap((q: string) => runSearch$(q))
);
```

Same semantics as `.do` — observer-shaped side effect, same value flows through unchanged.

`flatMap` was an alias for `mergeMap`; `flatMapLatest` was an alias for `switchMap`. v7 drops the aliases — use the canonical names. For a typeahead you want `switchMap` (cancel previous inner).

```ts
import { Observable } from 'rxjs';
import { debounceTime, distinctUntilChanged, switchMap } from 'rxjs/operators';

interface Pokemon {
  id: number;
  name: string;
}

declare function findPokemon$(q: string): Observable<Pokemon[]>;
declare const query$: Observable<string>;

export const pokemon$: Observable<Pokemon[]> = query$.pipe(
  debounceTime(250),
  distinctUntilChanged(),
  switchMap((q: string) => findPokemon$(q))
);
```

If you genuinely want merged parallelism (e.g. rare: firing off multiple independent requests concurrently), reach for `mergeMap` with an explicit `concurrency` arg — never reach for `flatMap` in modern code.

```ts
